      "content": "## Summary\nDespite the incredible dedication, time, and resources that all Gro DAO contributors and members have poured into this community and protocol over the past three years, Gro DAO finds itself facing challenges that cannot be ignored. The difficult market, underperformance of the Gro protocol, and key departures in the Groda Pod have put Gro DAO at a critical juncture, requiring a decision on its future. \n\nThis proposal outlines three main options: \n(1) Unwind the Protocol and the DAO, providing a clear exit strategy for stakeholders\n(2) Unwind the Protocol, Streamline Product Building, allowing for focused and leaner product development\n(3) Reject all options, which has two outcomes: either leaving the DAO without technical capabilities and continuing automated strategies without issue monitoring (Outcome A) or resulting in new proposals to be put up for vote (Outcome B).\n\nSee [[GRFC] - Gro DAO Strategic Path Forward](https://community.gro.xyz/t/grfc-gro-dao-strategic-path-forward/599) for full details and an in-depth analysis and discussion of each option. \n\n\n## Voting Options\n**Option 1. Unwind the Protocol and the DAO:**\n- Immediate unwinding of both Gro protocol and Gro DAO.\n- Groda Pod will focus on unwinding the protocol with a 3-month extension and a budget of 180,000 USDC.\n- Users can withdraw assets indefinitely, and treasury will be distributed via a redemption contract.\n\n**Option 2. Unwind the Protocol, Streamline Product Building:**\n- Immediate unwinding of the existing Gro protocol.\n- Groda Pod will be extended for 6 months with a budget of 245,000 USDC and 350,000 $GRO.\n- Focus on new product development, with bi-weekly reports to the DAO.\n\n**Option 3. Reject all options:**\n- No budget allocation for Groda Pod, leading to a lack of technical capabilities within the DAO.\n- Two potential outcomes for Option 3:\n-- Outcome A (Default): Continue automated strategies and stop issue monitoring, leaving no room for an orderly future wind-down.\n-- Outcome B: Open the door for new proposals to come up, allowing for the consideration of strategies not previously assessed.\n\n## Implementation\n**Option 1: Unwind the Protocol and the DAO**\n- Protocol Wind-down: Halt all Gro protocol strategies and switch to withdrawal-only mode.\n- Treasury Consolidation: Withdraw all assets from protocols and consolidate into USDC.\n- GRO Collection and Redemption: Implement a smart contract for GRO collection and redemption, allowing stakeholders to claim their share of the DAO treasury.\n- User Support: Actively assist users in exiting the protocol and redeeming assets.\n- Execution Team: Groda Pod, with a 3-month extension and a budget of 180,000 USDC.\n\n**Option 2: Unwind the Protocol, Streamline Product Building**\n- Protocol Dismantling: Stop all Gro protocol strategies and switch to withdrawal-only mode.\n- New Product Development: Initiate the development of a synthetic asset generator backed by staked ETH.\n- Bi-weekly Reporting: Regular updates to the DAO on progress, challenges, and next steps.\n- Team Scaling: Groda Pod will scale back its team size, focusing on efficiency.\n- Execution Team: Streamlined Groda Pod, with a 6-month extension and a budget of 245,000 USDC and 350,000 $GRO.\n\n**Option 3: Reject all options**\n- Outcome A (Default): Continue automated strategies and stop issue monitoring, leaving no room for an orderly future wind-down. No extension of Groda.\n- This option comes with a set of potential repercussion effects. \n-- Lack of User Support: Limited ability to assist users with unresolved issues or asset withdrawal.\n-- Operational Risks: Automated strategies may run unchecked, potentially leading to financial losses or system vulnerabilities.\n-- Market Volatility Risks: No active management to address market volatility or emergency situations, such as asset de-pegging.\n- Outcome B: Open the door for new proposals, allowing for the consideration of strategic paths not previously assessed following the standard governance process of the Gro DAO.\n\n## Pros\n- Option 1: Clear exit strategy, asset redemption for stakeholders.\n- Option 2: Potential for new product-market fit, leaner operation.\n- Option 3: Keeps all options open for future strategies.\n\n## Cons\n- Option 1: Loss of community and product.\n- Option 2: Continued operational risk and financial expenditure.\n- Option 3: Lack of technical capabilities, increased operational risks.\n\n## Timeline & Budget\n- Option 1: 3 months, 180,000 USDC\n- Option 2: 6 months, 245,000 USDC + 350,000 $GRO\n- Option 3: No immediate timeline or budget",
